import {Fragment as _Fragment, jsx as _jsx, jsxs as _jsxs} from "react/jsx-runtime";
export let _markdown = "\n\n# ChIA-PET Mode CLI\n\nChIA-PET (Chromatin Interaction Analysis by Paired-End Tag sequencing) mode analyzes protein-mediated chromatin interactions using linker-based paired-end sequencing.\n\n## Overview\n\nChIA-PET uses **bridge linkers** (biotinylated synthetic DNA sequences) during the ligation step. The Chr3D pipeline:\n\n1. **Linker Filtering** - Identifies and removes linker sequences from reads\n2. **Genomic Mapping** - Maps filtered reads to reference genome using BWA\n3. **PET Purifying** - Removes duplicates and merges overlapping PETs\n4. **PET Categorization** - Classifies into iPET (inter-ligation), sPET (self-ligation), oPET (other)\n5. **Peak Calling** - Calls peaks from sPET using MACS3\n6. **Loop Calling** - Identifies significant chromatin loops with FDR correction\n\n## Command\n\n```bash\nchr3d run --mode chiapet [options]\n```\n\n## Required Arguments\n\n| Argument         | Description                                     |\n| ---------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |\n| `--fastq-r1`     | Input R1 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)         |\n| `--fastq-r2`     | Input R2 FASTQ file (gzipped supported)         |\n| `--genome-index` | BWA-indexed reference genome FASTA              |\n| `--linker-a`     | Primary linker sequence (required for ChIA-PET) |\n| `--output-dir`   | Output directory                                |\n\n## Optional Arguments\n\n| Argument                 | Default  | Description                                           |\n| ------------------------ | -------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |\n| `--linker-b`             | None     | Secondary linker sequence (for dual-linker protocols) |\n| `--threads`              | 24       | Number of threads                                     |\n| `--use-bwa-mem`          | False    | Use BWA-MEM instead of BWA-ALN                        |\n| `--genome-size`          | `hs`     | Genome size for MACS3 (`hs`, `mm`, or number)         |\n| `--mapping-quality`      | 30       | Minimum mapping quality                               |\n| `--self-ligation-cutoff` | 8000     | Self-ligation distance cutoff (bp)                    |\n| `--extension-length`     | 500      | Tag extension length for clustering (bp)              |\n| `--ipet-threshold`       | 2        | Minimum iPET count for loops                          |\n| `--fdr-cutoff`           | 0.05     | FDR cutoff for significant loops                      |\n| `--sample-id`            | `sample` | Sample identifier                                     |\n| `--keep-intermediates`   | False    | Keep intermediate files                               |\n| `--keep-sam`             | False    | Keep SAM files                                        |\n| `--no-dedup`             | False    | Skip PCR duplicate removal                            |\n\n## Complete Example\n\n```bash\nchr3d run --mode chiapet \\\n    --fastq-r1 /data/sample_R1.fastq.gz \\\n    --fastq-r2 /data/sample_R2.fastq.gz \\\n    --genome-index /ref/hg38.fa \\\n    --linker-a ACGCGATATCTTATCTGACT \\\n    --linker-b AGTCAGATAAGATATCGCGT \\\n    --output-dir /output/chiapet_analysis \\\n    --threads 16 \\\n    --use-bwa-mem \\\n    --genome-size hs \\\n    --mapping-quality 30 \\\n    --self-ligation-cutoff 8000 \\\n    --extension-length 500 \\\n    --ipet-threshold 2 \\\n    --fdr-cutoff 0.05 \\\n    --sample-id CTCF_ChIAPET \\\n    --keep-intermediates\n```\n\n## Pipeline Steps\n\n### Step 1: Linker Filtering\n\nIdentifies linker sequences in reads using Smith-Waterman alignment and extracts genomic tags.\n\n```\nInput:  sample_R1.fastq.gz, sample_R2.fastq.gz\nOutput: step1_linker_filtering/filtered.*.R1.fastq\n        step1_linker_filtering/filtered.*.R2.fastq\n```\n\n**Linker Types:**\n\n* **1-1**: Both reads have linker A\n* **2-2**: Both reads have linker B\n* **1-2/2-1**: Chimeric (one of each)\n\n### Step 2: Genomic Mapping\n\nMaps linker-filtered reads to reference genome.\n\n```\nInput:  Filtered FASTQ files\nOutput: step2_mapping/mapped.dedup.bedpe\n```\n\n**Mapping Statistics:**\n\n* Total read pairs\n* Mapped pairs\n* Unique PETs (after deduplication)\n* Intra/inter-chromosomal ratios\n\n### Step 3: PET Purifying\n\nRemoves duplicates and merges overlapping PETs.\n\n```\nInput:  step2_mapping/mapped.dedup.bedpe\nOutput: step3_purifying/purified.merged.bedpe\n```\n\n### Step 4: PET Categorization\n\nClassifies PETs based on genomic distance and orientation.\n\n```\nInput:  step3_purifying/purified.merged.bedpe\nOutput: step4_categorization/categorized.ipet  (inter-ligation PETs)\n        step4_categorization/categorized.spet  (self-ligation PETs)\n        step4_categorization/categorized.opet  (other PETs)\n```\n\n**PET Categories:**\n\n* **iPET (Inter-ligation)**: Long-range interactions (distance > cutoff)\n* **sPET (Self-ligation)**: Short-range/same-fragment (distance ≤ cutoff)\n* **oPET (Other)**: Wrong orientation or unmapped\n\n### Step 5: Peak Calling\n\nCalls peaks from self-ligation PETs using MACS3.\n\n```\nInput:  step4_categorization/categorized.spet\nOutput: step5_peaks/peaks_peaks.narrowPeak\n        step5_peaks/peaks_summits.bed\n```\n\n### Step 6: Loop Calling\n\nIdentifies significant chromatin loops with statistical testing.\n\n```\nInput:  step4_categorization/categorized.ipet\nOutput: step6_loops/loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt\n```\n\n**Sub-steps:**\n\n1. **Pre-clustering**: Extends tags and creates initial clusters\n2. **Anchor clustering**: Merges overlapping clusters into anchors\n3. **Statistical significance**: Poisson-based test with FDR correction\n\n## Output Files\n\n```\noutput_dir/\n├── step1_linker_filtering/\n│   ├── filtered.1_1.R1.fastq\n│   ├── filtered.1_1.R2.fastq\n│   └── linker_stats.txt\n├── step2_mapping/\n│   ├── mapped.dedup.bedpe\n│   └── mapping_stats.txt\n├── step3_purifying/\n│   └── purified.merged.bedpe\n├── step4_categorization/\n│   ├── categorized.ipet\n│   ├── categorized.spet\n│   └── categorized.opet\n├── step5_peaks/\n│   ├── peaks_peaks.narrowPeak\n│   ├── peaks_summits.bed\n│   └── peaks_peaks.xls\n└── step6_loops/\n    ├── loops.cluster.filtered\n    └── loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt\n```\n\n## Output Format\n\n### Loop File Format (BEDPE)\n\nThe final loop file (`loops.cluster.FDRfiltered.txt`) contains:\n\n| Column      | Description                         |\n| ----------- | ----------------------------------- |\n| chr1        | Chromosome of anchor 1              |\n| start1      | Start position of anchor 1          |\n| end1        | End position of anchor 1            |\n| chr2        | Chromosome of anchor 2              |\n| start2      | Start position of anchor 2          |\n| end2        | End position of anchor 2            |\n| iPET\\_count | Number of supporting iPETs          |\n| expected    | Expected count (background)         |\n| distance    | Genomic distance                    |\n| p\\_value    | Raw p-value                         |\n| FDR         | Benjamini-Hochberg adjusted p-value |\n\n## Common Linker Sequences\n\n| Protocol      | Linker A               | Linker B               |\n| ------------- | ---------------------- | ---------------------- |\n| ChIA-PET Tool | `ACGCGATATCTTATCTGACT` | `AGTCAGATAAGATATCGCGT` |\n| ENCODE        | `GTTGGATAAG`           | `GTTGGAATGT`           |\n\n## Tips\n\n1. **Linker Quality**: Ensure linker sequences match your protocol exactly\n2. **Mapping Quality**: Use `--mapping-quality 30` for high-confidence interactions\n3. **Self-ligation Cutoff**: Adjust based on your protein's expected interaction range\n4. **FDR Threshold**: Use 0.05 for discovery, 0.01 for high-confidence loops\n5. **Memory**: For large datasets, ensure sufficient RAM (>32GB recommended)\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### Low linker detection rate\n\n* Verify linker sequences match your protocol\n* Check FASTQ quality scores\n* Try lowering alignment score threshold\n\n### Few significant loops\n\n* Increase sequencing depth\n* Check peak calling results (need peaks for enrichment)\n* Verify protein binding (ChIP-seq validation)\n\n### High duplicate rate\n\n* May indicate low library complexity\n* Consider deeper sequencing or library optimization\n";
